{"title_page": "Zaitun Driwaru", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan politician}}\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Zaitun Driwaru \n| image =\n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1977|12|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Yumbe District]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  =  '''[[Mvara Secondary School]]'''<br/>[[High School Diploma]]<br/>'''Muni National Teachers College'''<br/>[[Education|Diploma in Secondary Education]]<br/>'''[[Islamic University in Uganda]]'''<br/>[[Bachelor of Public Administration]]\n| occupation                = School Teacher, Politician \n| years_active              = 1999\u2013present\n| nationality               = Ugandan\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = Uganda\n| known_for                 = Politics\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Yumbe]]\n| title                     = [[Parliament of Uganda|Member of Parliament]] for [[Yumbe District|Yumbe District Women Constituency]]\n| website                   = \n| spouse                    = {{small|''' '''}}\n}}\n\n'''Zaitun Driwaru''' (born 10 December 1977), is a [[Uganda]]n [[school teacher]] and [[politician]], who serves as the District  Woman Representative for [[Yumbe District]], in the [[Parliament of Uganda|10th Ugandan Parliament]] (2016 - 2021).<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|title=Parliament of Uganda Members of the 10th Parliament: Zaitun Driwaru |publisher=[[Parliament of Uganda]] | url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=51 | date=2016 | author=Parliament of Uganda |access-date=23 April 2020 | location=Kampala}}</ref><ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|date=12 March 2016 |url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Driwaru-elected-Yumbe-Woman-MP/688334-3113168-wiaxogz/index.html | title=Driwaru Elected Yumbe Woman MP |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |author=Robert Elema |access-date=23 April 2020 | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nDriwaru was born on 10 December 1977. She attended Arua Hill Primary School, in the city of [[Arua]], the largest urban centre in the [[West Nile sub-region]]. She graduated from there in 1991 and enrolled at [[Mvara Secondary School]] also in Arua. She obtained both her [[Uganda Certificate of Education]] (O-Level) and her [[Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education]] (A-Level) from Mvara, in 1995 and 1999, respectively.<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\nShe was admitted to ''Muni National Teachers College'', where she was awarded a [[Education|Diploma in Secondary Education]], in 2002. In 2005, she graduated from the [[Islamic University in Uganda]], with a degree of [[Bachelor of Public Administration]].<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Before politics===\nFrom 1999 until 2001, was a sales manager at [[Bata (company)| Bata Uganda]]. She then served as a secondary school teacher at ''Aringa Secondary School'', in the town of [[Yumbe]]. She then served as a Community Development Officer for [[Yumbe District| Yumbe District Local Government]], from 2006 until 2011.<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\n===As a politician===\nDuring the 2016 parliamentary elections, Zaitun Driwaru contested for the seat of District Woman Representative for Yumbe District. She ran as an independent candidate. Driwaru beat Avako Naima Gule, of the ruling [[National Resistance Movement]] political party, who was the incumbent MP at that time. Driwaru received 32,504 votes against Naima's 24,394.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1419263/yumbe-police-tear-gas-post-election-fracas |title=Yumbe Police Fire Tear Gas In Post-Election Fracas |newspaper=[[New Vision]] | date=10 March 2016 |author=New Vision |access-date=23 April 2020 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn the 10th Parliament, she serves on the committee on education and sports and the committee on government assurances.<ref name=\"1R\"/> She is also a member of the ''Uganda Women Parliamentary Association'' (UWOPA).<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://uwopa.or.ug/content/members-uwopa-10th-parliament | title=Members of UWOPA In the 10th Ugandan Parliament |date=2016 |publisher=Uganda Women Parliamentary Association |access-date=23 April 2020 |author=Uganda Women Parliamentary Association | place=Kampala}}</ref> Zaitun Driwaru is a full member of the foundation body of the ''Uganda Muslim Supreme Council'' (UMSC).<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[New Vision]] | url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:YAJ8l5In1xIJ:https://www.parliament.go.ug/cmis/browser%3Fid%3Ddbea72ae-88cb-43af-8b93-1f7a2c9b2444%253B1.0+&cd=4&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ug |title=Muslim MPs Plan Bill On Family Law |date=5 July 2019 |author=Farooq Kasule |access-date=23 April 2020 |location=Kampala | format=Cached from the original on 23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nusura Tiperu]]\n* [[Rose Atima Ayaka]]\n* [[Peace Proscovia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.parliament.go.ug/ Website of the Parliament of Uganda]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driwaru, Zaitun}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yumbe District]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Muslims]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Islamic University in Uganda alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Nile sub-region]]\n[[Category:People educated at Mvara Secondary School]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Independent Ugandan politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan politician}}\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Zaitun Driwaru \n| image =\n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1977|12|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Yumbe District]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  =  '''[[Mvara Secondary School]]'''<br/>[[High School Diploma]]<br/>'''Muni National Teachers College'''<br/>[[Education|Diploma in Secondary Education]]<br/>'''[[Islamic University in Uganda]]'''<br/>[[Bachelor of Public Administration]]\n| occupation                = School Teacher, Politician \n| years_active              = 1999\u2013present\n| nationality               = Ugandan\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = Uganda\n| known_for                 = Politics\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Yumbe]]\n| title                     = [[Parliament of Uganda|Member of Parliament]] for [[Yumbe District|Yumbe District Women Constituency]]\n| website                   = \n| spouse                    = {{small|''' '''}}\n}}\n\n'''Zaitun Driwaru''' (born 10 December 1977), is a [[Uganda]]n [[school teacher]] and [[politician]], who serves as the District  Woman Representative for [[Yumbe District]], in the [[Parliament of Uganda|10th Ugandan Parliament]] (2016 - 2021).<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|title=Parliament of Uganda Members of the 10th Parliament: Zaitun Driwaru |publisher=[[Parliament of Uganda]] | url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=51 | date=2016 | author=Parliament of Uganda |access-date=23 April 2020 | location=Kampala}}</ref><ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|date=12 March 2016 |url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Driwaru-elected-Yumbe-Woman-MP/688334-3113168-wiaxogz/index.html | title=Driwaru Elected Yumbe Woman MP |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |author=Robert Elema |access-date=23 April 2020 | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nDriwaru was born on 10 December 1977. She attended Arua Hill Primary School, in the city of [[Arua]], the largest urban centre in the [[West Nile sub-region]]. She graduated from there in 1991 and enrolled at [[Mvara Secondary School]] also in Arua. She obtained both her [[Uganda Certificate of Education]] (O-Level) and her [[Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education]] (A-Level) from Mvara, in 1995 and 1999, respectively.<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\nShe was admitted to ''Muni National Teachers College'', where she was awarded a [[Education|Diploma in Secondary Education]], in 2002. In 2005, she graduated from the [[Islamic University in Uganda]], with a degree of [[Bachelor of Public Administration]].<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Before politics===\nFrom 1999 until 2001, was a sales manager at [[Bata (company)| Bata Uganda]]. She then served as a secondary school teacher at ''Aringa Secondary School'', in the town of [[Yumbe]]. She then served as a Community Development Officer for [[Yumbe District| Yumbe District Local Government]], from 2006 until 2011.<ref name=\"1R\"/>\n\n===As a politician===\nDuring the 2016 parliamentary elections, Zaitun Driwaru contested for the seat of District Woman Representative for Yumbe District. She ran as an independent candidate. Driwaru beat Avako Naima Gule, of the ruling [[National Resistance Movement]] political party, who was the incumbent MP at that time. Driwaru received 32,504 votes against Naima's 24,394.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1419263/yumbe-police-tear-gas-post-election-fracas |title=Yumbe Police Fire Tear Gas In Post-Election Fracas |newspaper=[[New Vision]] | date=10 March 2016 |author=New Vision |access-date=23 April 2020 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn the 10th Parliament, she serves on the committee on education and sports and the committee on government assurances.<ref name=\"1R\"/> She is also a member of the ''Uganda Women Parliamentary Association'' (UWOPA).<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://uwopa.or.ug/content/members-uwopa-10th-parliament | title=Members of UWOPA In the 10th Ugandan Parliament |date=2016 |publisher=Uganda Women Parliamentary Association |access-date=23 April 2020 |author=Uganda Women Parliamentary Association | place=Kampala}}</ref> Zaitun Driwaru is a full member of the foundation body of the ''Uganda Muslim Supreme Council'' (UMSC).<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[New Vision]] | url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:YAJ8l5In1xIJ:https://www.parliament.go.ug/cmis/browser%3Fid%3Ddbea72ae-88cb-43af-8b93-1f7a2c9b2444%253B1.0+&cd=4&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ug |title=Muslim MPs Plan Bill On Family Law |date=5 July 2019 |author=Farooq Kasule |access-date=23 April 2020 |location=Kampala | format=Cached from the original on 23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nusura Tiperu]]\n* [[Rose Atima Ayaka]]\n* [[Peace Proscovia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.parliament.go.ug/ Website of the Parliament of Uganda]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driwaru, Zaitun}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yumbe District]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Muslims]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Islamic University in Uganda alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Nile sub-region]]\n[[Category:People educated at Mvara Secondary School]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Independent Ugandan politicians]\n", "name_user": "Fsmatovu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zaitun_Driwaru"}
